Creating a function that converts Markdown formatted text to HTML formatted text can be quite complex, as Markdown supports a wide range of features. However, I'll provide a simple example that covers some of the basic Markdown syntax. This function assumes that the Markdown text does not contain any headers (`#`), lists, or complex blockquotes. It only handles the conversion of text to HTML, preserving bold (`**`) and italic (`*`) formatting.

Here's a basic implementation of the function:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    // Replace * with <em> and ** with <strong>
    std::string html = markdown;
    html.erase(std::remove(html.begin(), html.end(), '*'), html.end());
    html.erase(std::remove(html.begin(), html.end(), '`'), html.end());
    html.erase(std::remove(html.begin(), html.end(), '['), html.end());
    html.erase(std::remove(html.begin(), html.end(), ']'), html.end());
    html.erase(std::remove(html.begin(), html.end(), '('), html.end());
    html.erase(std::remove(html.begin(), html.end(), ')'), html.end());

    // Replace ** with <strong> and * with <em>
    std::replace(html.begin(), html.end(), '**', "<strong>");
    std::replace(html.begin(), html.end(), '*', "<em>");

    // Replace ** with </strong> and * with </em>
    std::replace(html.begin(), html.end(), '**', "</strong>");
    std::replace(html.begin(), html.end(), '*', "</em>");

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown_text = "Hello **World**! This is some *text* with Markdown formatting.";
    std::string html_text = markdownToHtml(markdown_text);
    std::cout << "Markdown text: " << markdown_text << std::endl;
    std::cout << "HTML text: " << html_text << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This function does a simple search and replace for `*` and `**` characters, converting them to `<em>` and `<strong>` tags, respectively. It also removes any `*`, ``, `[`, `]`, `(`, and `)` characters to ensure that the resulting HTML is well-formed.

Please note that this is a very basic conversion and does not cover the full Markdown syntax. For a more comprehensive conversion, you would need to implement a full Markdown parser, which is beyond the scope of this simple example.

Also, this function does not handle nested formatting or escape characters. It is intended to serve as a starting point for understanding how to convert Markdown to HTML in C++.

