In LaTeX, footnotes are typically used for additional comments or references within the text. However, if you want to create a footnote that lists all the authors of a document, you can use the `\footnote` command within the `\author` command of the `article` or `book` document class. Here's how you can do it:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\author{Author One\footnote{First Author's Footnote} \and
Author Two\footnote{Second Author's Footnote} \and
Author Three\footnote{Third Author's Footnote}}

\title{Title of the Document}

\maketitle

\end{document}
```

In this example, each author has their own footnote that will appear at the bottom of the page. The `\and` command is used to separate the authors in the `\author` command.

If you want to create a single footnote that lists all the authors, you can use the `\footnote` command within the `\author` command and include the authors' names within braces:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\author{Author One \and
Author Two \and
Author Three}

\title{Title of the Document}

\maketitle

\begin{center}
\footnote{This is a footnote that lists all the authors: Author One, Author Two, and Author Three.}
\end{center}

\end{document}
```

In this case, the footnote appears at the bottom of the page after the title and contains the list of all authors.

Remember that when using footnotes, it's good practice to include a space after the author's name before the footnote marker `[^1]` to prevent the footnote from being too close to the author's name.

If you are using a bibliography management tool like `biblatex` or `bibtex`, you can also include the authors' names in the bibliography entries and use the `\cite` command to cite them in the text, which will automatically generate a reference in the bibliography.

C++ program to find the nth Fibonacci number using dynamic programming:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>

int fibonacci(int n) {
    std::vector<int> fibonacci_sequence(n + 1);
    fibonacci_sequence[0] = 0;
    fibonacci_sequence[1] = 1;

    for (int i = 2; i <= n; ++i) {
        fibonacci_sequence[i] = fibonacci_sequence[i - 1] + fibonacci_sequence[i - 2];
    }

    return fibonacci_sequence[n];
}

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the value of n: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    std::cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is: " << fibonacci(n) << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This program defines a function `fibonacci` that uses dynamic programming to find the nth Fibonacci number. It stores the Fibonacci sequence in a vector and calculates each subsequent number by adding the previous two. The `main` function prompts the user to enter the value of `n` and then calls the `fibonacci` function to find and print the nth Fibonacci number.

C++ program to find the nth Fibonacci number using recursion:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

// Function to find the nth Fibonacci number using recursion
int fibonacci(int n) {
    // Base case: if n is 0 or 1, the nth Fibonacci number is n itself
    if (n == 0 || n == 1) {
        return n;
    }
    // Recursive case: find the nth Fibonacci number by adding the previous two
    return fibonacci(n - 1) + fibonacci(n - 2);
}

// Driver code to test the function
int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter the value of n: ";
    cin >> n;

    // Call the function to find the nth Fibonacci number
    int fibNumber = fibonacci(n);

    // Print the result
    cout << "The " << n << "th Fibonacci number is: " << fibNumber << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This program defines a function `fibonacci` that takes an integer `n` as input and returns the `n`th Fibonacci number. The function uses a base case to handle when `n` is 0 or 1, and a recursive case to find the Fibonacci number for `n - 1` and `n - 2` and then add them together.

The `main` function prompts the user to enter the value of `n`, calls the `fibonacci` function with the entered value, and prints the result.

To compile and run this program, save it as a `.cpp` file and use a C++ compiler. When you run the program, it will ask for the value of `n`, and then print out the `n`th Fibonacci number.

